# Comprehensive Programming Course: From Novice to Software Architect

## Course Overview

**Title:** Mastering Software Development: From Beginner to Architect  
**Duration:** 12 Modules (Self-paced, approximately 6-9 months)  
**Project:** Build a complete, sellable 3D Board Game Application using Java and JavaFX  
**Target Audience:** Complete beginners with no programming experience

---

## MODULE 1: Setting Up Your Development Environment & Understanding the Big Picture

### Learning Objectives
- Set up a professional development workstation
- Understand what software engineering is and why it matters
- Install and configure all necessary tools
- Create your first "Hello World" program

### Topics Covered

#### 1.1 What is Software Engineering?
- The difference between programming and software engineering
- Why software engineering matters for professional projects
- The software development life cycle overview
- Basic terminology: requirements, design, development, testing, deployment, maintenance

**Real-World Example:** Think of building a house vs. just stacking bricks. Software engineering is the architectural plan, foundation, plumbing, electrical—everything that makes the house functional and maintainable.

#### 1.2 Setting Up Your Workstation
- Hardware requirements (64-bit computer, 8GB+ RAM recommended)
- Downloading and installing Java Development Kit (JDK)
- Installing NetBeans IDE (Integrated Development Environment)
- Installing new media tools (GIMP for graphics, Audacity for audio)

**Practice:** Follow the step-by-step installation guide for your operating system. Verify everything works by running a simple "Hello World" application.

#### 1.3 Your First Java Program
- Understanding the main() method
- System.out.println()
- Compiling and running your code
- Understanding basic Java syntax

**Practice:** Write a program that prints "Hello, World!" and your name. Then modify it to print a short message about what you hope to build.

#### 1.4 Understanding Project Structure
- What is a project?
- Source folders, packages, and classes
- The JavaFXGame project template

**Lab Activity:** Create your first JavaFX project in NetBeans. Run it and see the blank window.

