package helloworld;

/**
 * This is my first Java program.
 * It prints a greeting to the console.
 */
public class HelloWorld {

    /**
     * The main method is where the program starts.
     */
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Print a message
        System.out.println("Hello, World!");
    }
}
```

### Explanation Line by Line

- **`package helloworld;`** – Every Java file belongs to a package (like a folder). This organizes your code.
- **`public class HelloWorld`** – Defines a class named `HelloWorld`. A class is a blueprint for objects. For now, think of it as a container for your program.
- **`public static void main(String[] args)`** – This is the **main method**. When you run the program, Java starts executing the code inside this method.
- **`System.out.println("Hello, World!");`** – This line prints the text `Hello, World!` to the console (the output window).
- **`// Print a message`** – This is a **comment**. The computer ignores it, but it helps humans understand the code.

