## 2.1 Making Decisions: The `if` Statement

In programming, we often need to make decisions based on conditions. The `if` statement allows us to execute code only when a condition is true.

### Syntax

```java
if (condition) {
    // code to run if condition is true
}
```

### Example

```java
int score = 85;

if (score >= 70) {
    System.out.println("You passed!");
}
```

### `if-else`

```java
if (score >= 70) {
    System.out.println("You passed!");
} else {
    System.out.println("You failed.");
}
```

### `else if` (multiple conditions)

```java
if (score >= 90) {
    System.out.println("Grade: A");
} else if (score >= 80) {
    System.out.println("Grade: B");
} else if (score >= 70) {
    System.out.println("Grade: C");
} else {
    System.out.println("Grade: F");
}
```

### Logical Operators

- `&&` – AND (both must be true)
- `||` – OR (at least one must be true)
- `!` – NOT (reverses boolean)

**Example**:
```java
int age = 25;
boolean hasLicense = true;

if (age >= 18 && hasLicense) {
    System.out.println("You can drive.");
}
```

---

## 2.2 The `switch` Statement

When you have many discrete values to check, `switch` can be cleaner than multiple `if-else`.

### Syntax

```java
switch (variable) {
    case value1:
        // code
        break;
    case value2:
        // code
        break;
    default:
        // code if no case matches
}
```

### Example

```java
int day = 3;
String dayName;

switch (day) {
    case 1:
        dayName = "Monday";
        break;
    case 2:
        dayName = "Tuesday";
        break;
    case 3:
        dayName = "Wednesday";
        break;
    default:
        dayName = "Invalid day";
}

System.out.println(dayName);
```

---

## 2.3 Loops: Repeating Code

Loops allow us to run a block of code multiple times.

### `while` Loop

The `while` loop repeats as long as a condition is true.

```java
int i = 0;
while (i < 5) {
    System.out.println(i);
    i++;   // increment i by 1
}
// Output: 0, 1, 2, 3, 4
```

### `do-while` Loop

This is similar, but the condition is checked after the code runs, so the code runs at least once.

```java
int i = 0;
do {
    System.out.println(i);
    i++;
} while (i < 5);
```

### `for` Loop

The `for` loop is used when you know how many times to repeat.

```java
for (int i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
    System.out.println(i);
}
```

**Parts**:
- `int i = 0;` – initialization (runs once)
- `i < 5;` – condition (checked before each iteration)
- `i++` – increment (runs after each iteration)

---

## 2.4 Avoiding Infinite Loops

An infinite loop never ends. For example:

```java
int i = 0;
while (i < 5) {
    System.out.println(i);
    // forgot to increment i!
}
```

Always ensure the loop condition will eventually become false.

