## 4.1 Inheritance Basics

Inheritance allows a class to inherit fields and methods from another class. This promotes code reuse and establishes a hierarchy.

**Terminology**:
- **Superclass (parent)** – The class being inherited from.
- **Subclass (child)** – The class that inherits.

### Example

```java
// Superclass
public class GameObject {
    protected int x, y;   // position on board
    protected String name;

    public GameObject(String name, int x, int y) {
        this.name = name;
        this.x = x;
        this.y = y;
    }

    public void move(int dx, int dy) {
        x += dx;
        y += dy;
    }

    public void display() {
        System.out.println(name + " at (" + x + "," + y + ")");
    }
}

// Subclass
public class Player extends GameObject {
    private int health;
    private int score;

    public Player(String name, int x, int y) {
        super(name, x, y);   // call superclass constructor
        health = 100;
        score = 0;
    }

    // Additional methods
    public void takeDamage(int damage) {
        health -= damage;
    }

    // Override display
    @Override
    public void display() {
        super.display();  // call parent's display
        System.out.println("Health: " + health + " Score: " + score);
    }
}
```

### Using Inheritance

```java
Player p = new Player("Alice", 0, 0);
p.move(2, 3);   // inherited from GameObject
p.takeDamage(10);
p.display();
```

---

## 4.2 Overriding Methods

When a subclass provides its own implementation of a method from the superclass, it's called **overriding**. Use `@Override` annotation to indicate it (optional but good practice).

**Rules**:
- Method name, parameters, and return type must match.
- Access level cannot be more restrictive (e.g., public overridden method cannot become private).

---

## 4.3 Abstract Classes

An abstract class cannot be instantiated; it is meant to be subclassed. It can have abstract methods (no body) that subclasses must implement.

```java
public abstract class GameObject {
    protected int x, y;
    public abstract void update();  // must be implemented by subclasses
}

public class Player extends GameObject {
    @Override
    public void update() {
        // logic for player update
    }
}
```

---

## 4.4 Interfaces

An interface is a contract that specifies what methods a class must implement. It contains only method signatures (and constants). Classes can implement multiple interfaces.

```java
public interface Drawable {
    void draw();
}

public interface Movable {
    void move(int dx, int dy);
}

public class Player extends GameObject implements Drawable, Movable {
    @Override
    public void draw() {
        // draw player on screen
    }

    @Override
    public void move(int dx, int dy) {
        // move logic
    }
}
```

---

## 4.5 Polymorphism

Polymorphism means "many forms". It allows you to treat objects of different classes through a common superclass or interface.

```java
List<GameObject> objects = new ArrayList<>();
objects.add(new Player("Alice", 0, 0));
objects.add(new Enemy("Goblin", 5, 5));

for (GameObject obj : objects) {
    obj.update();  // works for any subclass
}
```

---

