## 9.1 Animation in JavaFX

JavaFX provides `Transition` subclasses for common animations.

- `RotateTransition` – rotate a node.
- `TranslateTransition` – move a node.
- `ScaleTransition` – scale a node.
- `FadeTransition` – fade in/out.
- `ParallelTransition` – combine animations.
- `SequentialTransition` – run animations one after another.

### Example: Rotate a sphere

```java
import javafx.animation.RotateTransition;
import javafx.util.Duration;

RotateTransition rt = new RotateTransition(Duration.seconds(2), sphere);
rt.setByAngle(360);
rt.setCycleCount(1);
rt.play();
```

---

## 9.2 Project Step: Spinner for Topic Selection

We'll create a spinner (a sphere with text) that rotates and stops on a quadrant.

### Create Spinner Node

```java
Sphere spinner = new Sphere(60);
PhongMaterial spinMat = new PhongMaterial();
Image spinTexture = new Image("file:spin_texture.png");  // texture with "SPIN" text
spinMat.setDiffuseMap(spinTexture);
spinner.setMaterial(spinMat);
spinner.setTranslateX(0);
spinner.setTranslateY(0);
spinner.setTranslateZ(100);
```

### Animation to Spin

```java
RotateTransition spinnerSpin = new RotateTransition(Duration.seconds(3), spinner);
spinnerSpin.setAxis(Rotate.Y_AXIS);
spinnerSpin.setByAngle(1080);  // 3 full rotations
spinnerSpin.setCycleCount(1);
spinnerSpin.setOnFinished(event -> {
    // Determine which quadrant landed
    int quadrant = (int) (spinner.getRotate() % 360 / 90);
    // Highlight that quadrant
});
spinnerSpin.play();
```

